#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:10
msgid "3.1 Defining the Objective: Low Energy for Real Data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:12
msgid ""
"The preceding chapters have introduced two essential perspectives: the "
"<b>probabilistic framework</b> of statistical physics (Chapter 1) and the"
" <b>architectural principles</b> of recurrent neural networks (Chapter "
"2). We now unite these perspectives under the umbrella of <b>Energy-Based"
" Models (EBMs)</b> . This section defines the core learning objective "
"that drives all energy-based models, including the Boltzmann machine: to "
"shape the energy landscape so that real data resides in deep valleys, "
"while all other configurations occupy higher ground."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:14
msgid "<b>The Energy-Based Modeling Paradigm</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:16
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"An energy-based model is defined by a scalar <b>energy function</b> "
"$E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})$, parameterized by $ \\theta$, that assigns a "
"real-valued energy to every possible configuration $\\mathbf{x}$ of the "
"variables of interest. For a Boltzmann machine, $\\mathbf{x}$ represents "
"the joint state of visible and hidden units, but the framework applies "
"broadly to any structured configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:18
msgid ""
"The energy function induces a probability distribution via the "
"<b>Boltzmann distribution</b> (or Gibbs distribution):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:20
msgid ""
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) = "
"\\frac{\\exp\\left(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})\\right)}{Z_\\theta}, \\quad "
"\\text{where} \\quad Z_\\theta = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:22
msgid ""
"This formulation accomplishes a fundamental transformation: <b>low energy"
" corresponds to high probability</b>. The model assigns higher likelihood"
" to configurations that it deems \"good\" or \"compatible\" according to "
"its internal criteria."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:24
msgid ""
"Crucially, the energy function is <b>unnormalized, </b>it provides a "
"relative ordering of configurations but does not directly yield "
"probabilities without the partition function $Z_\\theta$. This is both a "
"strength (flexibility in designing energy functions) and a challenge "
"(intractability of $Z_\\theta$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:26
msgid "<b>The Learning Objective: Maximum Likelihood and KL Divergence</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:28
msgid ""
"Given a training dataset $\\mathcal{D} = \\{\\mathbf{x}^{(1)}, "
"\\mathbf{x}^{(2)}, \\ldots, \\mathbf{x}^{(M)}\\}$ drawn independently "
"from an unknown data distribution $P_{\\text{data}}(\\mathbf{x})$, the "
"goal of learning is to adjust the parameters $ \\theta$ so that the model"
" distribution $P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})$ approximates $P_{\\text{data}}$ as"
" closely as possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:30
msgid ""
"The standard criterion for this approximation is <b>maximum likelihood "
"estimation (MLE)</b>. We seek parameters that maximize the probability of"
" the observed data under the model:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:32
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\theta^* = \\arg\\max_\\theta \\prod_{m=1}^M "
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}^{(m)}) = \\arg\\max_\\theta \\sum_{m=1}^M \\log "
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}^{(m)})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:34
msgid "Equivalently, we minimize the <b>negative log-likelihood</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:36
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\mathcal{L}(\\theta) = -\\frac{1}{M} \\sum_{m=1}^M \\log "
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}^{(m)})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:38
msgid "Substituting the Boltzmann distribution form of $P_\\theta$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:40
#, python-brace-format
msgid "\\log P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) = -E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) - \\log Z_\\theta"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:42
msgid "Thus, the negative log-likelihood becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:44
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\mathcal{L}(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{M} \\sum_{m=1}^M "
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}^{(m)}) + \\log Z_\\theta"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:46
msgid "This decomposition reveals the two competing forces that shape learning:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:48
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Data term</b>: $\\frac{1}{M} \\sum_{m} E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}^{(m)})$, "
"the average energy of real data points. Minimizing this term pushes the "
"energy of observed data <b>downward</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:49
msgid ""
"<b>Partition function term</b>: $\\log Z_\\theta$, the log of the sum of "
"exponentials of negative energies over all configurations. Minimizing "
"this term pushes the energy of <b>all</b> configurations, and especially "
"those with currently low energy, <b>upward</b>, because $\\log Z_\\theta$"
" grows as more configurations acquire low energy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:51
msgid ""
"The learning process is therefore a <b>tug-of-war</b>: the data term "
"pulls down the energy at the observed data points, while the partition "
"function term pushes up the energy everywhere else to maintain "
"normalization. The equilibrium of this tug-of-war is reached when the "
"model distribution matches the data distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:53
msgid "Connection to KL Divergence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:55
msgid ""
"The MLE objective has a deeper interpretation from information theory. "
"Minimizing the negative log-likelihood is <b>equivalent</b> to minimizing"
" the <b>Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence</b> from the data distribution "
"to the model distribution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:57
msgid ""
"\\text{KL}(P_{\\text{data}} \\parallel P_\\theta) = "
"\\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} P_{\\text{data}}(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}) \\log"
" "
"\\frac{P_{\\text{data}}(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})}{P_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:59
msgid "This can be rewritten as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:61
msgid ""
"\\text{KL}(P_{\\text{data}} \\parallel P_\\theta) = "
"-\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}}[\\log P_\\theta(\\mathbf{X})] - "
"H(P_{\\text{data}})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:63
msgid ""
"where $H(P_{\\text{data}}) = -\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}}[\\log "
"P_{\\text{data}}(\\mathbf{X})]$ is the entropy of the data distribution "
"(a constant independent of $\\theta$). Therefore, minimizing "
"$\\text{KL}(P_{\\text{data}} \\parallel P_\\theta)$ is equivalent to "
"maximizing the expected log-likelihood $f(\\theta)$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:65
msgid ""
"f(\\theta) = \\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}}[\\log P_\\theta(\\mathbf{X})] = "
"\\frac{1}{M} \\sum_{m=1}^M \\log P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}^{(m)})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:67
msgid ""
"This equivalence reveals that <b>MLE is fundamentally about matching "
"distributions, </b>which means the model distribution $P_\\theta$ is "
"trained to be as close as possible to the empirical data distribution in "
"the sense of KL divergence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:69
msgid "Gradient of the Log-Likelihood"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:71
msgid ""
"To perform gradient-based optimization, we compute the gradient of the "
"log-likelihood $f(\\theta)$ with respect to the parameters:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:73
msgid ""
"\\nabla f(\\theta) = \\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}}[\\nabla \\log "
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{X})] = -\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}}[\\nabla "
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{X})] - \\nabla \\log Z_\\theta"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:75
msgid "The gradient of $\\log Z_\\theta$ is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:77
msgid ""
"\\nabla \\log Z_\\theta = \\frac{1}{Z_\\theta} "
"\\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} \\exp(-E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})) "
"\\nabla E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}) = \\mathbb{E}_\\theta[\\nabla "
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{X})]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:79
msgid "Thus, the gradient of the log-likelihood becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:81
msgid ""
"\\nabla f(\\theta) = -\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}}[\\nabla "
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{X})] + \\mathbb{E}_\\theta[\\nabla "
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{X})]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:83
msgid ""
"This contrastive form, i.e. the difference between an expectation under "
"the <b>data distribution</b> and an expectation under the <b>model "
"distribution,</b> is the mathematical heart of all Boltzmann machine "
"learning algorithms. The first term lowers the energy of observed data "
"configurations; the second term raises the energy of configurations that "
"the model currently deems probable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:85
msgid "Special Case: Visible-Only Boltzmann Machine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:87
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"For a Boltzmann machine with only visible units (no hidden units), the "
"gradient simplifies to a particularly transparent form. Substituting the "
"energy function $E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) = -\\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{x} "
"- \\frac{1}{2} \\mathbf{x}^\\top \\mathbf{W} \\mathbf{x}$ and taking the "
"derivative with respect to a weight $w_{ij}$ yields:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:89
msgid ""
"\\frac{\\partial f(\\theta)}{\\partial w_{ij}} = \\langle X_i X_j "
"\\rangle_{\\text{data}} - \\langle X_i X_j \\rangle_{\\text{model}}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:91
msgid ""
"where $\\langle X_i X_j \\rangle_{\\text{data}}$ is the expected product "
"of the activities of units $i$ and $j$ when the visible units are clamped"
" to the data (the positive phase), and $\\langle X_i X_j "
"\\rangle_{\\text{model}}$ is the expected product when the network "
"samples freely from its equilibrium distribution (the negative phase). "
"This simple expression directly captures the essence of contrastive "
"learning: co-activations observed in the data are reinforced, while those"
" generated by the model’s own fantasies are suppressed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:93
msgid "<b>Geometric Intuition: Sculpting the Energy Landscape</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:95
msgid ""
"Imagine the energy landscape as a deformable surface over the space of "
"all configurations. Initially, the surface may be flat (all "
"configurations have similar energy and probability) or arbitrarily "
"wrinkled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:97
msgid "Learning proceeds by iteratively applying two operations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:99
msgid ""
"<b>Excavation</b>: At the locations of training examples, we dig "
"downward, which lowering the energy to create basins of attraction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:100
msgid ""
"<b>Elevation</b>: Everywhere else, we raise the landscape to prevent the "
"model from assigning high probability to regions where no data resides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:102
msgid ""
"The <b>gradient</b> of the log-likelihood with respect to the parameters "
"$\\theta$formalizes this intuition:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:104
msgid ""
"\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\theta} = -\\frac{1}{M} \\sum_{m=1}^M "
"\\frac{\\partial E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}^{(m)})}{\\partial \\theta} + "
"\\mathbb{E}_{P_\\theta} \\left[ \\frac{\\partial "
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})}{\\partial \\theta} \\right]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:106
msgid ""
"The first term is the negative average gradient of the energy at the data"
" points, the direction of steepest descent for lowering data energy. The "
"second term is the expected gradient of the energy under the model's own "
"distribution, the direction that would lower the energy of configurations"
" the model currently favors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:108
msgid ""
"The positive sign on the second term means that, overall, we move "
"parameters in the direction that <b>increases</b> <b>energy</b> where the"
" model currently puts probability mass. This is the mathematical "
"expression of tug-of-war."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:110
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Note on notation</b>: In many textbooks, the negative log-likelihood "
"$\\mathcal{L}(\\theta)$ is minimized. Here we maximize $f(\\theta) = "
"-\\mathcal{L}(\\theta)$ to keep the gradient sign consistent with the "
"contrastive divergence algorithm introduced in Section [3.3 Contrastive "
"Divergence](/kpp-theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-"
"ebms-cd)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:112
msgid "<b>Why Low Energy for Real Data?</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:114
msgid ""
"The mandate \"low energy for real data\" is not an arbitrary choice; it "
"follows directly from the maximum likelihood principle and the "
"exponential link between energy and probability. But beyond mathematics, "
"this objective carries several intuitive and practical advantages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:116
msgid ""
"<b>Unnormalized Flexibility</b>: The energy function can be designed "
"without concern for normalization. Any differentiable function of the "
"configuration can serve as an energy. This allows incorporating domain "
"knowledge, constraints, and structured architectures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:117
msgid ""
"<b>Natural Handling of Uncertainty</b>: In regions where no data has been"
" observed, the model's energy can remain high, corresponding to low "
"probability. The model is not forced to make arbitrary predictions in "
"unobserved regions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:118
msgid ""
"<b>Generation by Descent</b>: Once trained, new samples can be generated "
"by starting from a random configuration and following a stochastic "
"descent procedure on the energy landscape. This yields configurations "
"that are typical under the learned distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:119
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Compositionality</b>: Energy functions can be combined additively. If "
"$E_1(\\mathbf{x})$ and $E_2(\\mathbf{x})$ model different aspects of the "
"data, the sum $E_1 + E_2$ defines a product of experts model that "
"captures both constraints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:120
msgid ""
"<b>Physical Plausibility</b>: The energy-based view connects learning to "
"well-understood physical processes like annealing and phase transitions, "
"providing a rich conceptual vocabulary for understanding model behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:122
msgid "<b>The Challenge: The Partition Function Gradient</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:124
msgid ""
"The elegance of the energy-based objective comes at a computational cost."
" The gradient involves an expectation under the model distribution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:126
msgid ""
"\\mathbb{E}_{P_\\theta} \\left[ \\frac{\\partial "
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})}{\\partial \\theta} \\right] = "
"\\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} P_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}) "
"\\frac{\\partial E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})}{\\partial \\theta}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:128
msgid ""
"This sum over all possible configurations is intractable for any non-"
"trivial model. We cannot compute it exactly, nor can we enumerate all "
"configurations to approximate it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:130
msgid ""
"This intractability is the central computational challenge that defines "
"the field of energy-based learning. Every practical algorithm for "
"training Boltzmann machines can be understood as a strategy for "
"approximating this model expectation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:132
msgid "The subsequent sections will explore these strategies in depth:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:134
msgid ""
"<b>Section </b>[3.2 The Intractable Partition Function Problem](/kpp-"
"theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition) "
"formalizes the partition function problem and its implications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:135
msgid ""
"<b>Section </b>[3.3 Contrastive Divergence](/kpp-theoretical-foundations"
"\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd) introduces <b>contrastive "
"divergence</b>, the breakthrough approximation that made Boltzmann "
"machines practical."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:136
msgid ""
"<b>Chapters 4 and beyond</b> develop specific architectures (Restricted "
"Boltzmann Machines) and training algorithms that exploit structural "
"constraints to make the model expectation tractable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:138
msgid "<b>Connection to Discriminative Learning</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:140
msgid ""
"It is instructive to contrast the energy-based generative objective with "
"the more familiar <b>discriminative</b> objective used in feedforward "
"classifiers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:142
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"In a discriminative model, such as a logistic regression or a multilayer "
"perceptron classifier, we model the conditional distribution $P(y \\mid "
"\\mathbf{x})$ directly, without modeling the input distribution "
"$P(\\mathbf{x})$. The energy function is defined over the joint space "
"$(\\mathbf{x}, y)$, and the probability of a label given an input is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:144
msgid ""
"P(y \\mid \\mathbf{x}) = \\frac{\\exp(-E(\\mathbf{x}, y))}{\\sum_{y'} "
"\\exp(-E(\\mathbf{x}, y'))}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:146
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Crucially, the partition function now sums only over the possible labels "
"$y'$ for a fixed input $\\mathbf{x}$. This sum is typically tractable "
"(e.g., over a finite set of classes). The intractable sum over all "
"configurations $\\mathbf{x}$ is <b>not required</b> for discriminative "
"training."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:148
msgid ""
"This observation explains why discriminative models have been so "
"successful in supervised learning: they circumvent the partition function"
" bottleneck entirely. However, they pay a price: they cannot generate new"
" inputs, complete missing data, or learn from unlabeled examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:150
msgid ""
"Energy-based generative models embrace the full complexity of the "
"partition function because they aim to model the entire data "
"distribution, not just the decision boundary between classes. The reward "
"is a richer, more flexible model capable of unsupervised learning, "
"generation, and inference in any direction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:152
msgid "<b>Summary</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:154
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Energy-Based Models</b> define a probability distribution via "
"$P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) \\propto \\exp(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}))$, linking"
" low energy to high probability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:155
msgid ""
"The learning objective is <b>maximum likelihood</b>, which decomposes "
"into minimizing the average energy of data while controlling the "
"partition function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:156
msgid ""
"The gradient of the log-likelihood $f(\\theta)$ involves a <b>data "
"term</b> (easy to compute) and a <b>model expectation</b> (intractable to"
" compute exactly)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:157
msgid ""
"Learning is geometrically interpreted as <b>sculpting the energy "
"landscape</b>: lowering basins at data points while raising the "
"surrounding terrain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-def.md:158
